Black Lives Matter Media Analysis

J. Nathan Matias (blog) (/u/natematias) (twitter).

July 26, 2017

  • Hypotheses
  • Data Collection
  • Findings
    • Changes in News Coverage

Hypotheses

H1. CHANCE OF COVERAGE: Unarmed black people killed by the police received more coverage in the news after the death of Michael Brown, a change declined over time.

  • H1A. The chance that an unarmed black person killed by the police would receive at least one news story about them increased after the death of Michael Brown.

  • H1B. The incidence rate of news stories published about an unarmed black person killed by the police increased after the death of Michael Brown and declined from that point onward.

H2. FRAMING: News stories about unarmed black people killed by the police were more likely to frame those deaths in terms of a systemic issue, as measured by the number of other previous deaths mentioned in the article.

  • H2A: The chance that an article mentioned at least one other victim increased after the death of Michael Brown

  • H2B: The incidence rate of articles framed as a systemic issue increased after the death of Michael Brown and declined from that point onward

Data Collection

(TODO: describe the MediaCloud process) (draw from Allan Kos documentation)

The dataset of unarmed black people killed by the police or who died in police custody (people) includes a total of 343 people killed from Jan 04, 2013 to Jun 29, 2016. Within this dataset, Michael Browns death occurred on Aug 09, 2014, the 581th day in the dataset. After removing Michael Brown and any people killed in the 14 day period before and including the day of his death, our dataset includes 333 people.

In our analysis of media coverage received by peoples deaths (H1), our dependent variable is the number of articles about a victim in the 14 days after their death. We also observe the binary measure of whether the victim was mentioned in any articles in our sample during the same period. ince MediaCloud may collect varying percentages of the available articles, and since the output of articles by publishers varies over time, we normalize this measure by dividing the raw by the number of articles observed on MediaCloud that day

Within the dataset of people, we also observe the number of days that elapsed since the first observation in the dataset (day.num), as well as whether a person was killed in the period after Michael Browns death (after.brown). We record the male or female gender of the victim, as reported in the news articles, their age, and the log-transformed population of the metropolitan area where the person was killed (ln.population).

The dataset of stories about unarmed black people killed by the police (stories) includes 11,114 stories. Stories are included in the dataset if (LIST OTHER CRITERIA), if at least one of the people they mention was killed by the police within the two week period before the story was published. Since many people killed within a two week period also appeared in the same articles, we associate each article with the person who was most recently killed at the time the article was published. The dataset omits 6913 stories about Michael Brown.

In our story-level analysis (H2), our dependent variable is the count of sentences in the story that mention at least one prior victim in the dataset (sentences.about.others), as well as a binary measure of whether any sentence in the article mentioned any other prior victim (wider.issue).

Findings

Changes in News Coverage

Chance of News Coverage

To test the hypothesis of an increase in news coverage after the death of Michael Brown, we use a logistic regression model to estimate the chance that a person killed by the police or who died in their custody would have at least one article mention their name. To improve the precision of our estimate of the difference, we include regression adjustments for the gender of the person as reported in the news, their reported age, and the population of metropolitan area where their death occurred.

We find that in the 580 days before Michael Browns death, a 33 year old black male killed by the police in a city with the median population had a 39.34% chance of having at least one article published about them, on average. In the 691 days after Browns death, a similar person had a 64.25% chance of having an article published about them on average, a statistically-significant difference of 24.92 percentage pionts (p=0.00003).

Incidence Rate of News Coverage

We also test the hypothesis of an increase in the incidence rate of coverage of black people killed by the police, one that declines over time. To test this hypothesis, we use a negative binomial model that predicts the incidence rate of the normalized number of articles published about a person in the 14 day period after their death (Long, J. Scott). In the model, we test the hypothesis of a cubic relationship between the day count and the incidence rate, controlling for age, gender, and population:

(TODO: formula)

In the model of stories per person (Table N), we find that the incidence rate increased to a maximum rate between 152 and 61 at a time 312 days after Michael Browns death. After this day, the rate declined on average. By the end of our observation period, the incidence rate of stories has declined to the point that 95% confidence intervals overlap with thase at the beginning of our sample, and the difference between them is not statistically-significant.

Frame Changes

Chance of Including A Wider Frame

To test the hypothesis of a change in the framing of stories after the death of Michael Brown, we use a logistic regression model to estimate the chance of a story to include a mention of at least one other person. To improve the precision of our estimate of the difference, we include regression adjustments for the gender of the person as reported in the news, their reported age, and the population of metropolitan area where their death occurred.

In a logistic regression mode on the 11,114 stories in our sample, in the 580 days before Michael Browns death, we find that for an unarmed, 33 year old black male killed by the police in a city of median size, a story had a 2.44% chance of mentioning a previous victim on average. In the 688 days after Michael Browns death, a similar story had a 20.71% chance of including at least one mention of another victim on average, an estimated difference of 18.26 percentage points.

  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent) +

            size=7, color="gray40", fontface="bold") +
  scale_x_discrete("", labels = c("Before Michael Brown's Death","After Michael Brown's Death")) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = lwr, ymax = upr), width=0.1) +
  theme(panel.grid.major = element_blank(), panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
        panel.background = element_blank(), axis.line.x = element_line(size=1, colour = "black"),
        axis.line.y = element_line(size=1, colour = "black"), axis.ticks = element_line(size=1),

Incidence Rate of Including Other Names

We also test the frame-change hypothesis by estimating changes in the incidence rate of mentions of other victims in stories, expecting that the rate would increase after the death of Michael Brown and declines over time. To test this hypothesis, we use a negative binomial model that predicts the incidence rate of sentences mentioning other victims, for stories published about a person in the 14 day period after their death (Long, J. Scott). In the model, we test the hypothesis of a cubic relationship between the day count and the incidence rate, as well as a change in that relationship after the death of Michael Brown, controlling for age, gender, and population:

(include model formula here)

In the model of stories per person (Table below), we find that the incidence rate of other victims mentioned in stories did increase after the death of Michael Brown to an estimate between 1.92 and 3.04. The rate then declined on average after Michael Browns death. By the end of our observation period, the incidence rate had declined to an estimated value of 0.17, which was still greater than the incidence rate of 0.00 at the beginning of the observation period, a difference that is statistically-significant.
